sec.p:
Two main data sources are used in this article. First, data was derived from a research project called ‘Close to the body’, which studies the practical and ethical issues related to medical textiles. The project was conducted in co-operation between National Institute for Health and Welfare and University of Art and Design Helsinki (currently Aalto University School of Art and Design). The project data included:


Online catalogues that market medical textiles (240 clothing items, of which 10 were patient overalls) to the Finnish care institutions;

photographs (n = 12) of patient overalls used by dementia patients on a hospital ward;

interviews with designers of medical textiles (n = 14, working for 10 different companies);

interviews of people with experience of wearing medical textiles, or their regular visitors in the care institutions.
